\section{Two trend flavors}{

The studies do \strong{not} use the same estimator here, and the difference is
substantive rather than cosmetic:

\describe{
\item{\code{trend = "continuous"} (resource_extraction)}{
\verb{logit <ind> Trend} then \verb{margins, eydx(Trend) predict(pr)} and
\verb{nlcom (_b[Trend]*100)}. Emits a \strong{semi-elasticity}: percent change in the
probability per year. Only the pooled share (\code{GLSS0}) accompanies it.}
\item{\code{trend = "wave_diff"} (land_tenure)}{
\verb{logit <ind> i.Survey} then \verb{margins Survey} and
\verb{nlcom ((_b[6bn.Survey]-_b[7.Survey])*100)}. Emits a \strong{percentage-point}
difference between two waves, and per-wave shares accompany it.
Note the sign: it is \strong{earlier minus later}, so an indicator that grew
reports a negative value. Land's Table 2 shows \verb{Not owned = -9.743} while
the share rose from 0.290 to 0.388. That is the convention, not an error.}
}

Mixing them up yields plausible numbers on the wrong scale -- percent per year
versus percentage points -- so \code{trend} has no default.
